00:03:47.480 --> 00:03:49.300
So we start with a
photovoltaic cell.

00:03:49.300 --> 00:03:51.790
You're familiar with
the sun putting photons

00:03:51.790 --> 00:03:54.850
on the semiconductor material
and making electricity.

00:03:54.850 --> 00:03:59.380
There's another field
called thermophotovoltaics,

00:03:59.380 --> 00:04:03.160
or TPV, where we have an
intermediate body which

00:04:03.160 --> 00:04:04.930
receives the heat--
the heat can come

00:04:04.930 --> 00:04:08.860
from any conventional
sources or solar.

00:04:08.860 --> 00:04:11.260
And this body at--

00:04:11.260 --> 00:04:14.980
right now, what we're doing is
around 1,000 degrees Celsius,

00:04:14.980 --> 00:04:17.610
things start to glow red
around 600 degrees Celsius.

00:04:17.610 --> 00:04:19.070
So this is very hot.

00:04:19.070 --> 00:04:20.290
It radiates photons.

00:04:20.290 --> 00:04:22.330
It glows red.

00:04:22.330 --> 00:04:25.300
And those photons-- and
then converts electricity

00:04:25.300 --> 00:04:28.190
by photovoltaic cells.

00:04:28.190 --> 00:04:32.590
So how many of you have
heard of Planck's law?

00:04:37.290 --> 00:04:39.240
OK.

00:04:39.240 --> 00:04:42.150
So Planck's law was
sort of the foundation

00:04:42.150 --> 00:04:47.460
of quantum mechanics in modern
science in the 20th century.

00:04:47.460 --> 00:04:49.560
And Planck's law
tells you how many

00:04:49.560 --> 00:04:53.880
photons come off
a heated surface

00:04:53.880 --> 00:04:56.620
and what wavelength they are.

00:04:56.620 --> 00:05:01.260
And so the photon
flux, the number

00:05:01.260 --> 00:05:05.880
of photons coming off that
surface per square centimeter

00:05:05.880 --> 00:05:06.990
is given by Planck's law.

00:05:06.990 --> 00:05:08.190
And we represent that here--

00:05:08.190 --> 00:05:09.990
1x Planck's law.

00:05:09.990 --> 00:05:11.790
And there were reasons
that we thought

00:05:11.790 --> 00:05:13.290
that if you brought
that real close,

00:05:13.290 --> 00:05:14.957
you could do near-field
coupling and you

00:05:14.957 --> 00:05:16.080
could exceed Planck's law.

00:05:16.080 --> 00:05:18.510
And it was somewhat
controversial in the beginning.

00:05:18.510 --> 00:05:23.370
In fact, in a meeting
with Hermann Haus,

00:05:23.370 --> 00:05:28.020
who was a real power house
in electrical engineering

00:05:28.020 --> 00:05:32.610
and photonics-- unfortunately,
passed away a few years ago--

00:05:32.610 --> 00:05:34.590
the first time we came
in his office with this,

00:05:34.590 --> 00:05:36.180
he said, forget it.

00:05:36.180 --> 00:05:39.690
He said, there's just no
way to violate Planck's law.

00:05:39.690 --> 00:05:43.080
And about an hour
later, he realized

00:05:43.080 --> 00:05:44.670
that we weren't
really violating it,

00:05:44.670 --> 00:05:48.750
that we were operating outside
of the limits of applicability

00:05:48.750 --> 00:05:51.960
that Planck himself
had put on the law.

00:05:51.960 --> 00:05:56.160
Planck's law says
that the geometry

00:05:56.160 --> 00:05:58.620
of all the pieces of the
system have to be large

00:05:58.620 --> 00:05:59.850
compared to the wavelength.

00:05:59.850 --> 00:06:02.280
And one of the geometric
pieces of the system

00:06:02.280 --> 00:06:04.240
is the space between
these two surfaces.

00:06:04.240 --> 00:06:06.810
So literally, the gap
between the hot surface

00:06:06.810 --> 00:06:08.970
and the photovoltaic surface.

00:06:08.970 --> 00:06:11.280
In MTPV, Micron gap
Thermal PhotoVoltaics,

00:06:11.280 --> 00:06:13.050
we put them really
close together,

00:06:13.050 --> 00:06:21.660
like 100 nanometers apart,
or 1/10 of a micron.

00:06:21.660 --> 00:06:24.750
And when you do that, you
get near-field coupling

00:06:24.750 --> 00:06:27.180
and the photon flux,
and therefore, the power

00:06:27.180 --> 00:06:31.210
out can dramatically go up by
about an order of magnitude.

00:06:31.210 --> 00:06:32.940
And so he said, oh OK.

00:06:32.940 --> 00:06:35.400
He said, so you actually want
to put the photovoltaic cell

00:06:35.400 --> 00:06:38.460
into the near-field or
evanescent field of this heated

00:06:38.460 --> 00:06:38.960
surface.

00:06:38.960 --> 00:06:40.380
And we said, yes, exactly.

00:06:40.380 --> 00:06:41.400
He said, OK.

00:06:41.400 --> 00:06:44.570
Well, maybe you can do
better than Planck's law.

00:06:44.570 --> 00:06:49.020
And so really this is the field
that we've been pioneering,

00:06:49.020 --> 00:06:55.200
using this mechanism which
basically derives from the fact

00:06:55.200 --> 00:06:57.930
that inside the hot
body, there are photons

00:06:57.930 --> 00:06:59.910
generated in every direction.

00:06:59.910 --> 00:07:02.430
It's only the photons
generated inside that come up

00:07:02.430 --> 00:07:03.720
to that surface--

00:07:03.720 --> 00:07:06.300
normal to the surface or
nearly normal to the surface--

00:07:06.300 --> 00:07:07.570
that actually get out.

00:07:07.570 --> 00:07:10.500
So in a hot body, most
of the photonic energy

00:07:10.500 --> 00:07:14.430
that's being generated all
the time is trapped inside.

00:07:14.430 --> 00:07:17.910
But if you bring a surface
up close enough to it,

00:07:17.910 --> 00:07:20.700
as those photons
approach the surface,

00:07:20.700 --> 00:07:24.030
a photon is-- as Professor
Haus pointed out-- actually

00:07:24.030 --> 00:07:26.928
has extent, it has
size of something

00:07:26.928 --> 00:07:28.220
on the order of the wavelength.

00:07:28.220 --> 00:07:31.830
So we don't usually think
of photons as having a size.

00:07:31.830 --> 00:07:33.340
But they have an
approximate size,

00:07:33.340 --> 00:07:34.590
something like the wavelength.

00:07:34.590 --> 00:07:38.100
The wavelength we're
working with is 2 microns.

00:07:38.100 --> 00:07:42.493
The gap here is only 0.1 micron,
so this big 2-micron photon

00:07:42.493 --> 00:07:44.160
comes traveling up
towards that surface,

00:07:44.160 --> 00:07:47.190
and just goes right across
this vacuum gap between the two

00:07:47.190 --> 00:07:48.930
surfaces, act as a
photovoltaic cell,

00:07:48.930 --> 00:07:50.830
and then can become power.

00:07:50.830 --> 00:07:54.330
So it's all the photons that
are impinging upon the surface

00:07:54.330 --> 00:07:58.470
off-normal that get into
the photovoltaic cell

00:07:58.470 --> 00:08:01.800
here, in our technology,
MTPV, that do not

00:08:01.800 --> 00:08:03.320
get out of that hot body.

00:08:03.320 --> 00:08:05.070
They're trapped inside
the hot body there.

00:08:05.070 --> 00:08:07.590
And that's what causes
this increase in power.

00:08:12.200 --> 00:08:14.620
So why do we bother doing that?

00:08:14.620 --> 00:08:19.600
We think that there are a number
of places of application--

00:08:19.600 --> 00:08:22.450
I think, in the course, you
guys have contemplated--

00:08:22.450 --> 00:08:25.780
or about to contemplate a number
of different sources of energy

00:08:25.780 --> 00:08:28.820
as well as uses of energy--

00:08:28.820 --> 00:08:32.260
so one of the application
domains is vehicles.

00:08:32.260 --> 00:08:34.390
And we'll come back to
this slide at the end

00:08:34.390 --> 00:08:36.490
to discuss it in a
little more detail.

00:08:36.490 --> 00:08:39.940
There's solar energy,
portable power, industrial,

00:08:39.940 --> 00:08:43.480
which is the first one that
we're working on right now.

00:08:43.480 --> 00:08:45.910
The other one not shown
is building power, a cogen

00:08:45.910 --> 00:08:47.340
for a building like this.

00:08:47.340 --> 00:08:49.720
So the first one is waste heat.

00:08:49.720 --> 00:08:54.010
There is lots of waste
heat in lots of places.

00:08:54.010 --> 00:08:56.590
The focus right now
for our technology

00:08:56.590 --> 00:08:58.840
is industrial waste
heat, the kinds of things

00:08:58.840 --> 00:09:03.910
that you see in these pictures,
specifically a glass plant.

00:09:03.910 --> 00:09:06.920
These are the basic modules.

00:09:06.920 --> 00:09:10.600
These are the chips of which you
saw a schematic a moment ago.

00:09:10.600 --> 00:09:13.630
So this is actually
a chip stack.

00:09:13.630 --> 00:09:17.290
Each one of these is a pair
of chips-- the hot chip

00:09:17.290 --> 00:09:20.060
and then below it, the
cold photovoltaic chip.

00:09:20.060 --> 00:09:22.420
So we build them into arrays.

00:09:22.420 --> 00:09:26.020
And then we take these
modules and we build those

00:09:26.020 --> 00:09:31.510
into arrays, like this, where
we have a housing on the outside

00:09:31.510 --> 00:09:36.460
and then the chips go on
a mounting and control

00:09:36.460 --> 00:09:40.210
substructure, if you will,
which is mounted inside

00:09:40.210 --> 00:09:42.070
of this hollow housing.

00:09:42.070 --> 00:09:46.750
So the hollow housing protects
from the outside combustion

00:09:46.750 --> 00:09:49.900
gases, et cetera, allows the
heat to go through the surface

00:09:49.900 --> 00:09:51.610
into the chips,
makes electricity.

00:09:51.610 --> 00:09:52.690
And that's it.

00:09:52.690 --> 00:09:56.650
It's a very modular technology.

00:09:56.650 --> 00:10:00.670
And that's one of
the promises of it,

00:10:00.670 --> 00:10:06.550
that it can be deployed-- we
call it kind of noninvasive.

00:10:06.550 --> 00:10:10.480
And you've talked about
disruptive technology

00:10:10.480 --> 00:10:13.540
some in the class,
which has become

00:10:13.540 --> 00:10:17.620
an important understanding
in the business of bringing

00:10:17.620 --> 00:10:19.660
all technology-- and not
even just technology,

00:10:19.660 --> 00:10:21.310
but products to market.

00:10:21.310 --> 00:10:24.190
And the idea of
disruptive technology

00:10:24.190 --> 00:10:25.990
is the new technology
comes along

00:10:25.990 --> 00:10:28.750
and it's not very
good, technically,

00:10:28.750 --> 00:10:31.030
compared to sort of
the incumbents that

00:10:31.030 --> 00:10:32.800
are on the market.

00:10:32.800 --> 00:10:36.880
But it finds a niche
where it can perform.

00:10:36.880 --> 00:10:39.880
Often the niche is
called noncompetition.

00:10:39.880 --> 00:10:42.460
So developing a product--
you look for a place

00:10:42.460 --> 00:10:44.200
where there is no competition.

00:10:44.200 --> 00:10:46.390
And this is an
example of a place

00:10:46.390 --> 00:10:48.550
where there is no computation.

00:10:48.550 --> 00:10:52.510
This sits outside a coal mine.

00:10:52.510 --> 00:10:55.030
Coal mines nowadays, they go
down in the ground, and then

00:10:55.030 --> 00:10:58.630
the coal-- and then the front,
the digging front, if you will,

00:10:58.630 --> 00:11:00.610
the interface between
the air and the mine

00:11:00.610 --> 00:11:02.320
and the coal that's
still on the ground,

00:11:02.320 --> 00:11:05.350
it comes down and then
proceeds horizontally.

00:11:05.350 --> 00:11:10.130
And one of the issues
with coal mines, as--

00:11:10.130 --> 00:11:12.242
is there anybody who
has not heard of a--

00:11:12.242 --> 00:11:13.700
let's see how do
we want to ask it?

00:11:13.700 --> 00:11:16.653
Has anyone heard of a
coal mine explosion?

00:11:16.653 --> 00:11:17.320
Raise your hand.

00:11:20.190 --> 00:11:20.760
OK.

00:11:20.760 --> 00:11:23.820
So most folks have heard
of coal mine explosion.

00:11:23.820 --> 00:11:27.640
So why the coal mines explode?

00:11:27.640 --> 00:11:29.266
Any guesses?

00:11:29.266 --> 00:11:30.016
AUDIENCE: Methane.

00:11:32.872 --> 00:11:33.747
BOB DIMATTEO: Please?

00:11:33.747 --> 00:11:35.060
AUDIENCE: Trapped methane.

00:11:35.060 --> 00:11:35.852
BOB DIMATTEO: Yeah.

00:11:35.852 --> 00:11:38.230
Trapped methane, exactly.

00:11:38.230 --> 00:11:40.660
Whenever you're digging
up coal, you also

00:11:40.660 --> 00:11:42.100
liberate trapped methane--

00:11:42.100 --> 00:11:44.290
natural gas-- very explosive.

00:11:44.290 --> 00:11:49.660
And so they go through lots of
ways of controlling the methane

00:11:49.660 --> 00:11:52.110
content in the air so that
the coal mine doesn't blow up.

00:11:52.110 --> 00:11:53.360
But they do blow up some time.

00:11:53.360 --> 00:11:55.570
And so what people have
started to do is drill down

00:11:55.570 --> 00:11:57.250
in front of the coal mine--

00:11:57.250 --> 00:11:59.800
there's this vertical face
that's coming horizontally

00:11:59.800 --> 00:12:00.580
under the ground--

00:12:00.580 --> 00:12:02.750
they drill down
into it like this

00:12:02.750 --> 00:12:05.340
and they liberate the
methane in front of that.

00:12:05.340 --> 00:12:07.090
And then what do they
do with the methane?

00:12:07.090 --> 00:12:09.590
Well, this is what they do with
methane, believe it or not--

00:12:09.590 --> 00:12:10.360
oftentimes.

00:12:10.360 --> 00:12:13.120
I mean, if it's big enough,
if it's stable enough,

00:12:13.120 --> 00:12:16.870
then they will actually
feed it into a combined

00:12:16.870 --> 00:12:21.260
cycle or some type of combustion
system to make electricity.

00:12:21.260 --> 00:12:23.890
But first of all, the
coal mine front is moving

00:12:23.890 --> 00:12:27.400
and steam turbines
don't like to be moved.

00:12:27.400 --> 00:12:29.980
And so that's why you
see this very portable

00:12:29.980 --> 00:12:32.710
looking infrastructure here,
that they actually move it

00:12:32.710 --> 00:12:35.668
as the coal mine is moving.

00:12:35.668 --> 00:12:37.210
And what they need
to do is they just

00:12:37.210 --> 00:12:38.650
need to destroy the methane.

00:12:38.650 --> 00:12:42.670
So here is methane being
destroyed in that inner pipe

00:12:42.670 --> 00:12:43.870
there.

00:12:43.870 --> 00:12:46.390
And the idea is to just
take panels like this,

00:12:46.390 --> 00:12:48.670
and to run them down
the middle of that tube

00:12:48.670 --> 00:12:50.710
and to turn that
into electricity.

00:12:50.710 --> 00:12:53.950
