where do you get a job?

00:36:35.485 --> 00:36:37.068
Do you really want
to do clean energy?

00:36:37.068 --> 00:36:38.530
There are no clean energy jobs.

00:36:38.530 --> 00:36:40.720
And I went to work in
the aircraft industry

00:36:40.720 --> 00:36:43.060
because I also taken Fred
McGarry's course here

00:36:43.060 --> 00:36:44.560
in composite materials
because I was

00:36:44.560 --> 00:36:46.300
interested in composite
materials for what?

00:36:46.300 --> 00:36:48.383
Why might you be interested
in composite materials

00:36:48.383 --> 00:36:51.220
if you're interested in energy?

00:36:51.220 --> 00:36:52.390
Wait a minute.

00:36:52.390 --> 00:36:54.130
We got to get somebody
else, John-Mario.

00:36:54.130 --> 00:36:55.480
Thank you.

00:36:55.480 --> 00:36:56.080
Come on.

00:36:56.080 --> 00:36:57.478
Kristin?

00:36:57.478 --> 00:36:58.810
AUDIENCE: Lightweight vehicles?

00:36:58.810 --> 00:36:59.977
BOB DIMATTEO: Yeah, exactly.

00:36:59.977 --> 00:37:00.610
Exactly.

00:37:00.610 --> 00:37:01.390
Right.

00:37:01.390 --> 00:37:02.500
Exactly.

00:37:02.500 --> 00:37:04.090
Yeah.

00:37:04.090 --> 00:37:07.210
And so they wanted to build
lightweight helicopters.

00:37:07.210 --> 00:37:12.265
And so later on, I
realized that I--

00:37:12.265 --> 00:37:14.140
wasn't so clear at the
time that I was really

00:37:14.140 --> 00:37:15.598
working on clean
energy-- you know,

00:37:15.598 --> 00:37:17.380
lightweight, strong
materials which

00:37:17.380 --> 00:37:22.150
are now going in lots of
airplanes and vehicles.

00:37:22.150 --> 00:37:24.980
And I thought I was in
the aircraft industry,

00:37:24.980 --> 00:37:27.460
but I was really working--
pursuing my interest

00:37:27.460 --> 00:37:29.890
in clean energy.

00:37:29.890 --> 00:37:34.000
And then another stint with
a company up the street,

00:37:34.000 --> 00:37:37.660
MITRE Corporation, another
spin-out out of MIT--

00:37:37.660 --> 00:37:39.610
well, Lincoln Lab
spun out of MIT,

00:37:39.610 --> 00:37:42.680
and MITRE spun out
of Lincoln Lab.

00:37:42.680 --> 00:37:49.030
And when we started to explore
some of these concepts--

00:37:49.030 --> 00:37:52.480
but I really wanted to try
to do things more directly

00:37:52.480 --> 00:37:58.900
and linked with sort of
energy as the food piece

00:37:58.900 --> 00:38:01.180
that Christopher mentioned.

00:38:01.180 --> 00:38:04.525
And sort of the notion
that if a home--

00:38:07.300 --> 00:38:10.080
if a home-- it's part of like--

00:38:10.080 --> 00:38:13.680
like what's an energy
system in a home?

00:38:13.680 --> 00:38:16.140
I know this is real
easy, but what's

00:38:16.140 --> 00:38:17.550
an energy system in a home?

00:38:20.150 --> 00:38:23.360
That every home in
the United States has?

00:38:23.360 --> 00:38:24.424
Yeah, Jacob?

00:38:24.424 --> 00:38:25.292
AUDIENCE: HVAC.

00:38:25.292 --> 00:38:26.160
BOB DIMATTEO: HVAC.

00:38:26.160 --> 00:38:27.030
Exactly.

00:38:27.030 --> 00:38:30.140
So make making heat, keep
people warm in the cold weather.

00:38:30.140 --> 00:38:32.697
And what's another energy
system in the home?

00:38:32.697 --> 00:38:33.638
AUDIENCE: An oven.

00:38:33.638 --> 00:38:34.430
BOB DIMATTEO: Oven.

00:38:34.430 --> 00:38:34.930
OK.

00:38:34.930 --> 00:38:36.430
And what might the
oven run off of?

00:38:36.430 --> 00:38:38.080
AUDIENCE: Natural
gas or electricity.

00:38:38.080 --> 00:38:38.630
BOB DIMATTEO: Or electricity.

00:38:38.630 --> 00:38:39.130
OK.

00:38:39.130 --> 00:38:41.640
So then electricity is
another energy system.

00:38:41.640 --> 00:38:45.950
So one thought is, what if there
was a food system in a home

00:38:45.950 --> 00:38:46.910
also--

00:38:46.910 --> 00:38:49.470
going back to
Christopher's point.

00:38:49.470 --> 00:38:53.450
And so just the notion of
the home as being the energy

00:38:53.450 --> 00:38:55.940
central of your
physical well-being--

00:38:55.940 --> 00:38:59.150
whether it's in the developed
world or developing countries,

00:38:59.150 --> 00:39:02.120
even more important perhaps,
in developing countries.

00:39:02.120 --> 00:39:05.330
Any rate-- so it made me
want to build a house.

00:39:05.330 --> 00:39:07.520
And I built a house while
I was working full-time

00:39:07.520 --> 00:39:08.780
and then built another one.

00:39:08.780 --> 00:39:12.710
And so then I did that
for about eight years.

00:39:12.710 --> 00:39:16.340
And we were leaders in
energy efficient housing--

00:39:16.340 --> 00:39:18.610
no surprise.

00:39:18.610 --> 00:39:21.500
And over the course of
time, we built some miles

00:39:21.500 --> 00:39:24.500
of roads and 150 homes.

00:39:27.380 --> 00:39:29.960
And then I went back
to graduate school

00:39:29.960 --> 00:39:34.040
to more specifically
concentrate directly

00:39:34.040 --> 00:39:36.860
on energy technology
and the kinds of issues

00:39:36.860 --> 00:39:39.600
that I talked about earlier.

00:39:39.600 --> 00:39:46.310
And that's what led to MTPV
with the professors here.

00:39:46.310 --> 00:39:49.130
And then there's a laboratory
across the street, Draper

00:39:49.130 --> 00:39:50.360
Laboratory--

00:39:50.360 --> 00:39:53.720
it used to be the MIT
Instrumentation Lab.

00:39:53.720 --> 00:39:59.680
And they called me up and
said, we saw your resume

00:39:59.680 --> 00:40:02.850
in the course 6 resume book.

00:40:02.850 --> 00:40:05.570
And now this was and--

00:40:05.570 --> 00:40:07.760
this is in 1996.

00:40:07.760 --> 00:40:11.240
And energy-- so how
important-- how hot

00:40:11.240 --> 00:40:13.820
a topic was energy in 1996?

00:40:13.820 --> 00:40:15.950
Not for those of us that
were working in the field

00:40:15.950 --> 00:40:18.330
and dedicated, but I mean,
do you guys have any sense?

00:40:18.330 --> 00:40:20.060
How old were you guys in 1996?

00:40:20.060 --> 00:40:21.640
Just a couple of
examples, ballpark?

00:40:21.640 --> 00:40:22.013
AUDIENCE: Six.

00:40:22.013 --> 00:40:22.386
AUDIENCE: Four.

00:40:22.386 --> 00:40:23.011
AUDIENCE: Five.

00:40:23.011 --> 00:40:24.350
BOB DIMATTEO: Six, seven, OK.

00:40:24.350 --> 00:40:28.040
So it wasn't on the top of
you guys' agenda, right?

00:40:28.040 --> 00:40:30.710
But do you have a sense of
like how relevant it is today?

00:40:30.710 --> 00:40:35.030
How much in the news it
is today versus in 1996?

00:40:35.030 --> 00:40:36.410
More now or less now?

00:40:36.410 --> 00:40:39.050
How many think it's
more now than then?

00:40:39.050 --> 00:40:40.070
OK.

00:40:40.070 --> 00:40:40.850
Yeah.

00:40:40.850 --> 00:40:44.772
So it certainly seems that way.

00:40:44.772 --> 00:40:46.760
But at any rate, there
were folks over there

00:40:46.760 --> 00:40:48.810
that thought energy
would be important.

00:40:48.810 --> 00:40:52.910
And so we started developing
this MTPV technology there.

00:40:52.910 --> 00:40:57.890
First analysis, the visit
the Professor Haus mentioned

00:40:57.890 --> 00:41:01.910
earlier here on campus, who once
he realized that you actually

00:41:01.910 --> 00:41:03.500
could do better
than Planck's law,

00:41:03.500 --> 00:41:05.240
that we weren't
violating Planck's law,

00:41:05.240 --> 00:41:07.400
that we were just operating
outside of the limits

00:41:07.400 --> 00:41:11.280
that Planck himself put
on his law, he said, OK,

00:41:11.280 --> 00:41:12.560
go run the numbers.

00:41:12.560 --> 00:41:14.930
So go back and crank
through Maxwell's equations

00:41:14.930 --> 00:41:16.430
and do all that stuff.

00:41:16.430 --> 00:41:18.650
And come back and tell
me how much more--

00:41:18.650 --> 00:41:22.040
how much better can you
do that Planck's law?

00:41:22.040 --> 00:41:27.770
And so with a tremendous team at
Draper Laboratory, many of whom

00:41:27.770 --> 00:41:31.470
we still work with
today, we did that.

00:41:31.470 --> 00:41:34.370
And then-- so this is part of--

00:41:34.370 --> 00:41:36.230
one of you guys here
mentioned starting

00:41:36.230 --> 00:41:38.240
in a larger company, right?

00:41:38.240 --> 00:41:42.530
What's it look like starting an
energy technology in a startup

00:41:42.530 --> 00:41:43.820
versus the larger company?

00:41:43.820 --> 00:41:47.073
In the larger company, there
is management to deal with.

00:41:47.073 --> 00:41:48.740
Management does the
resource allocation.

00:41:48.740 --> 00:41:51.090
And hopefully, which
was the case for us,

00:41:51.090 --> 00:41:52.730
they ask good questions.

00:41:52.730 --> 00:41:55.370
First they said, go
convince Professor Haus

00:41:55.370 --> 00:41:56.720
that you have it all right.

00:41:56.720 --> 00:41:59.550
So when the analysis was
done, then they said, OK.

00:41:59.550 --> 00:42:01.940
Now you're ready to
design experiments, start

00:42:01.940 --> 00:42:03.260
doing the experiments.

00:42:03.260 --> 00:42:05.270
We built tiny
chips, 2 millimeters

00:42:05.270 --> 00:42:10.730
by 2 millimeters-- so smaller
than half your baby fingernail.

00:42:10.730 --> 00:42:15.410
And sure enough, the effect
was there as the theory--

00:42:15.410 --> 00:42:17.075
as the analysis predicted.

00:42:17.075 --> 00:42:18.950
We published that in
Applied Physics Letters.

00:42:18.950 --> 00:42:21.270
The government got
interested-- somebody mentioned

00:42:21.270 --> 00:42:22.520
government funding or whatnot.

00:42:22.520 --> 00:42:25.340
That can be a very important
part of energy technology

00:42:25.340 --> 00:42:27.960
because how is energy--

00:42:27.960 --> 00:42:31.310
how is energy technology
different than, say, software?

00:42:31.310 --> 00:42:33.230
Than, say, iPhone app?

00:42:38.150 --> 00:42:38.910
Obeida?

00:42:38.910 --> 00:42:40.933
Do you want to take a shot?

00:42:40.933 --> 00:42:42.600
AUDIENCE: It's more
of you have to build

00:42:42.600 --> 00:42:46.138
your products [INAUDIBLE].

00:42:46.138 --> 00:42:46.930
BOB DIMATTEO: Yeah.

00:42:46.930 --> 00:42:48.780
AUDIENCE: You need the materials
to build your products.

00:42:48.780 --> 00:42:49.572
BOB DIMATTEO: Yeah.

00:42:49.572 --> 00:42:52.522
AUDIENCE: More capital
for startup [INAUDIBLE]

00:42:52.522 --> 00:42:53.597
from your own company.

00:42:53.597 --> 00:42:54.430
BOB DIMATTEO: Right.

00:42:54.430 --> 00:42:55.210
Exactly.

00:42:55.210 --> 00:42:55.930
Yeah.

00:42:55.930 --> 00:43:03.370
And so there was a recent book
written called Lean Startup.

00:43:03.370 --> 00:43:05.080
And so this-- the
following is basically

00:43:05.080 --> 00:43:07.690
a plug for the engineering
field, a plug for what

00:43:07.690 --> 00:43:08.950
many of you were doing.

00:43:08.950 --> 00:43:11.470
So this book called
Lean Startup--

00:43:11.470 --> 00:43:15.850
and the folks at HBS
and Sloan are very much

00:43:15.850 --> 00:43:18.100
aware of it, et cetera.

00:43:18.100 --> 00:43:22.630
But it turns out that
it's been kind of a hit

00:43:22.630 --> 00:43:28.210
and almost sort of a craze
in the innovation world.

00:43:28.210 --> 00:43:32.110
But he says in it
that he assumes

00:43:32.110 --> 00:43:37.730
that what they're trying
to do can be done.

00:43:37.730 --> 00:43:40.865
So in other words, if you're
making an app for the iPhone,

00:43:40.865 --> 00:43:42.820
you know that you can
actually produce it.

00:43:42.820 --> 00:43:44.060
It can actually do the thing.

00:43:44.060 --> 00:43:45.815
Do you do it this
way for this market?

00:43:45.815 --> 00:43:47.398
Do you do it this
way for this market?

00:43:47.398 --> 00:43:52.740
And that's where the war gets
lost or won in that world.

00:43:52.740 --> 00:43:55.760
But here in energy,
it's really not that way

00:43:55.760 --> 00:43:59.990
because there's no guarantee
that things can be done.

00:43:59.990 --> 00:44:02.540
Like we've seen
billions of dollars

00:44:02.540 --> 00:44:05.120
go into the liquid
biofuels-- which one of you

00:44:05.120 --> 00:44:07.430
guys mentioned-- recently.

00:44:07.430 --> 00:44:11.570
And it's turned out that
it's very hard to do--

00:44:11.570 --> 00:44:13.130
very hard to do.

00:44:13.130 --> 00:44:17.630
So it really it was a
technical impediment,

00:44:17.630 --> 00:44:19.740
which is dramatically
different than, say,

00:44:19.740 --> 00:44:22.070
if you're in the software
world, where you basically

00:44:22.070 --> 00:44:24.800
know that you can build
what you want to build.

00:44:24.800 --> 00:44:26.828
And so whether you're
think about starting

00:44:26.828 --> 00:44:28.370
your own businesses
or whether you're

00:44:28.370 --> 00:44:31.790
interacting with management
in some big business,

00:44:31.790 --> 00:44:37.790
that understanding of
applying the right questions

00:44:37.790 --> 00:44:39.152
know and the right rules--

00:44:39.152 --> 00:44:40.610
so if you're in an
energy business,

00:44:40.610 --> 00:44:42.770
you probably want
the engineers to be

00:44:42.770 --> 00:44:44.575
more involved in
management decisions

00:44:44.575 --> 00:44:46.700
than maybe if you were
doing software or something.

00:44:46.700 --> 00:44:48.620
What you really need
to know is, it's

00:44:48.620 --> 00:44:51.170
the marketing people
that need to drive--

00:44:51.170 --> 00:44:53.120
that need to drive the process.

00:44:56.645 --> 00:44:57.145
OK.

