And if you were smart, you
would ask me about some of that

00:46:52.060 --> 00:46:54.060
if you want, especially
the half of you thinking

00:46:54.060 --> 00:46:56.380
about starting businesses.

00:46:56.380 --> 00:46:59.800
And but anyway, Robert Rines--

00:46:59.800 --> 00:47:00.963
so he taught a course--

00:47:00.963 --> 00:47:02.380
it was taught out
of course 6, I'm

00:47:02.380 --> 00:47:05.590
not sure why for starting
like 50 years ago

00:47:05.590 --> 00:47:07.750
in innovation and patents.

00:47:07.750 --> 00:47:10.050
And I took that course.

00:47:10.050 --> 00:47:13.570
And he became our patent
attorney for MTPV Corporation

00:47:13.570 --> 00:47:17.540
until he passed away
a couple of years ago.

00:47:17.540 --> 00:47:22.600
So MIT is really all
over this technology.

00:47:22.600 --> 00:47:27.690
And I guess--

00:47:27.690 --> 00:47:29.440
Hiram said, you know,
you should tell them

00:47:29.440 --> 00:47:31.990
that you think that you
guys have the potential

00:47:31.990 --> 00:47:34.600
to get to 60%
efficiency and like

00:47:34.600 --> 00:47:36.728
a megawatt per square meter.

00:47:36.728 --> 00:47:38.770
And I hate talking about
those things-- it really

00:47:38.770 --> 00:47:40.390
is what keeps us going.

00:47:40.390 --> 00:47:42.730
I mean, these initial
niche markets,

00:47:42.730 --> 00:47:44.140
they don't keep you going.

00:47:44.140 --> 00:47:47.440
They keep you
focused so you know

00:47:47.440 --> 00:47:50.000
what you need to do when
you get up every day.

00:47:50.000 --> 00:47:51.250
But they don't keep you going.

00:47:51.250 --> 00:47:53.710
What keeps you going is a
larger vision about something

00:47:53.710 --> 00:47:56.950
that-- it doesn't have to
be as large as producing

00:47:56.950 --> 00:47:58.780
50% of the world's energy.

00:47:58.780 --> 00:48:01.810
But it's a larger vision as
to how what you're working on

00:48:01.810 --> 00:48:03.683
creates meaning.

