00:51:58.600 --> 00:52:04.810
This story starts in '87
with the Brundtland Report,

00:52:04.810 --> 00:52:08.200
a Commission chaired by
Gro Harlem Brundtland,

00:52:08.200 --> 00:52:11.410
a woman who was a former
prime minister of Norway, that

00:52:11.410 --> 00:52:13.690
coined the phrase
sustainable development

00:52:13.690 --> 00:52:16.870
and gave it the definition
that you see there.

00:52:16.870 --> 00:52:21.010
And in that first small bullet
is sort of the economist's

00:52:21.010 --> 00:52:22.160
interpretation.

00:52:22.160 --> 00:52:25.160
And that is the economy has
a certain set of assets,

00:52:25.160 --> 00:52:27.430
intellectual capital,
and physical capital,

00:52:27.430 --> 00:52:33.220
and the environment, and the
natural world, a set of stocks.

00:52:33.220 --> 00:52:36.340
And the notion is
you should pass on

00:52:36.340 --> 00:52:38.890
to be sustainable
a set of stocks

00:52:38.890 --> 00:52:42.610
that are as desirable as
the set you inherited.

00:52:42.610 --> 00:52:45.040
The first President Bush
called that stewardship.

00:52:45.040 --> 00:52:47.950
Since he was a Republican,
nobody used that term.

00:52:47.950 --> 00:52:51.700
But that's the concept, that you
have a certain set of assets.

00:52:51.700 --> 00:52:55.330
So you could say, for instance,
that economic development

00:52:55.330 --> 00:52:59.860
in 19th century Britain was
arguably sustainable, right?

00:52:59.860 --> 00:53:03.880
They burned all the coal, the
country was dirty as anything

00:53:03.880 --> 00:53:06.370
for decades, but
they came out of it

00:53:06.370 --> 00:53:09.070
with tangible capital,
intellectual capital,

00:53:09.070 --> 00:53:13.450
a whole set of other assets that
provided standard of living.

00:53:13.450 --> 00:53:19.340
Saudi Arabia is mostly spending
the oil money on consumption.

00:53:19.340 --> 00:53:20.920
So when the oil goes--

00:53:20.920 --> 00:53:24.640
British coal is long
gone, but Britain used it.

00:53:24.640 --> 00:53:28.120
And the issue is that when
the Saudi oil is gone,

00:53:28.120 --> 00:53:31.990
that generation is not
going to have the assets.

00:53:31.990 --> 00:53:33.430
Now it's a little vague, right?

00:53:33.430 --> 00:53:36.670
It doesn't distinguish
between intellectual capital

00:53:36.670 --> 00:53:38.530
and species.

00:53:38.530 --> 00:53:42.220
And it doesn't say
anything about poverty.

00:53:42.220 --> 00:53:46.750
And this question of the
future generations' own needs--

00:53:46.750 --> 00:53:49.750
I mean, if the future generation
wants to only play video games,

00:53:49.750 --> 00:53:52.490
then wiping out the
elephants won't matter.

00:53:52.490 --> 00:53:53.950
But if future
generations actually

00:53:53.950 --> 00:53:56.530
care a lot about
the natural world,

00:53:56.530 --> 00:53:59.480
then having great video
games is not very important.

00:53:59.480 --> 00:54:03.040
So if you don't know what their
needs are, it's a little tough.

00:54:03.040 --> 00:54:05.410
And you know I was once
interviewed and asked

00:54:05.410 --> 00:54:07.840
what I thought sustainable
development meant,

00:54:07.840 --> 00:54:09.990
and I gave the
Brundtland definition.

00:54:09.990 --> 00:54:11.590
And they said, is
that all, you mean?

00:54:11.590 --> 00:54:12.692
That's kind of narrow.

00:54:12.692 --> 00:54:13.900
And I said, what do you mean?

00:54:13.900 --> 00:54:15.817
They said, what about
sustainable communities,

00:54:15.817 --> 00:54:17.920
and sustainable lifestyles,
and sustainable--

00:54:17.920 --> 00:54:20.020
it's gotten to mean sort
of everything that's good

00:54:20.020 --> 00:54:21.400
and wholesome and green--

00:54:21.400 --> 00:54:22.330
and a little vague.

00:54:22.330 --> 00:54:26.350
But nonetheless, start with the
sustainable development notion.

00:54:26.350 --> 00:54:30.280
The next big event was
the 1992 Conference

00:54:30.280 --> 00:54:32.200
on Environment and Development.

00:54:32.200 --> 00:54:36.130
This was the conference that
led to the Framework Convention

00:54:36.130 --> 00:54:38.770
on Climate Change
and really started

00:54:38.770 --> 00:54:41.740
that conversation-- the Kyoto
Protocol and all of that.

00:54:41.740 --> 00:54:43.570
That was a big deal.

00:54:43.570 --> 00:54:46.130
172 governments participated.

00:54:46.130 --> 00:54:50.260
108 heads of state or
heads of government went.

00:54:50.260 --> 00:54:51.170
That's huge.

00:54:51.170 --> 00:54:53.440
And what came out of
it was a lot of paper.

00:54:53.440 --> 00:54:55.510
But the Framework Convention
on Climate Change,

00:54:55.510 --> 00:54:59.650
which really structured
all the subsequent debate.

00:54:59.650 --> 00:55:03.040
So now we come to
20 years later.

00:55:03.040 --> 00:55:05.930
And you've got this
whole UN machinery.

00:55:05.930 --> 00:55:09.520
And we ought to have
a conference Rio+20.

00:55:09.520 --> 00:55:13.750
Well, if the headline
was climate in 1992,

00:55:13.750 --> 00:55:16.840
the question is, what's
the headline now?

00:55:16.840 --> 00:55:20.230
And that leads to the green
growth discussion, right?

00:55:20.230 --> 00:55:23.390
So you began to get--

00:55:23.390 --> 00:55:25.450
beginning a few
years ago, you began

00:55:25.450 --> 00:55:28.480
to see staff papers
emerging talking

00:55:28.480 --> 00:55:31.300
about the green economy,
and green development,

00:55:31.300 --> 00:55:33.760
and green growth.

00:55:33.760 --> 00:55:36.910
Now I have to say,
I've read a lot of this

00:55:36.910 --> 00:55:39.940
and the definition is
not entirely clear.

00:55:39.940 --> 00:55:45.130
It is described as a subset
of sustainable development.

00:55:45.130 --> 00:55:48.700
And it seems to be that subset
of sustainable development

00:55:48.700 --> 00:55:52.540
strategies that doesn't
involve degradation

00:55:52.540 --> 00:55:55.750
of the natural
environment on the way.

00:55:55.750 --> 00:55:59.260
So the British
development wouldn't be--

00:55:59.260 --> 00:56:03.460
might be sustainable because
at the end of all that dirt,

00:56:03.460 --> 00:56:06.100
they had high living standards
and the prospect of higher

00:56:06.100 --> 00:56:10.720
living standards, but not green,
because the environment was

00:56:10.720 --> 00:56:12.520
degraded rather substantially.

00:56:12.520 --> 00:56:14.620
It recovered, but it was
degraded substantially

00:56:14.620 --> 00:56:18.280
in the process, and I'm sure
species were extinguished.

00:56:18.280 --> 00:56:21.430
So maybe you could do
fossil fuels and be green.

00:56:21.430 --> 00:56:23.980
I think so.

00:56:23.980 --> 00:56:28.590
But if you think about
alternative ways of doing

00:56:28.590 --> 00:56:30.340
sustainable development,
there's another--

00:56:30.340 --> 00:56:34.030
another part of the World Bank--

00:56:34.030 --> 00:56:36.490
the World Bank, the UN,
the OECD, and others

00:56:36.490 --> 00:56:37.990
are talking about green economy.

00:56:37.990 --> 00:56:40.870
If you go on the World Bank
website and you look carefully,

00:56:40.870 --> 00:56:44.410
you see papers on
inclusive growth.

00:56:44.410 --> 00:56:47.560
And that says, well, you
have to be sustainable,

00:56:47.560 --> 00:56:51.100
but you should focus on poverty.

00:56:51.100 --> 00:56:53.710
Green growth says, you
ought to be sustainable

00:56:53.710 --> 00:56:57.095
but you should focus
on the environment.

00:56:57.095 --> 00:56:57.595
OK.

00:57:00.650 --> 00:57:01.860
Where do you go from there?

00:57:01.860 --> 00:57:07.490
Well, this is what is sort
of the interesting thing.

00:57:07.490 --> 00:57:10.250
Particularly the UN
now argues that if you

00:57:10.250 --> 00:57:15.080
make very large
investments in going green,

00:57:15.080 --> 00:57:18.470
growth of living
standards will increase.

00:57:18.470 --> 00:57:22.800
The phrase that's used is,
"a new engine of growth."

00:57:22.800 --> 00:57:25.100
Now if you're a
cynical economist,

00:57:25.100 --> 00:57:27.800
you realize that
not only does that

00:57:27.800 --> 00:57:32.730
mean there's a free lunch, but
one we'd all be paid to eat,

00:57:32.730 --> 00:57:33.230
right?

00:57:33.230 --> 00:57:35.660
Going green will
raise living standards

00:57:35.660 --> 00:57:38.670
after a very short
period of time.

00:57:38.670 --> 00:57:43.340
So what I want to do is talk
a little bit about that.

00:57:43.340 --> 00:57:47.780
You can imagine how I
and others got engaged.

00:57:47.780 --> 00:57:50.630
This was sort of very--

00:57:50.630 --> 00:57:55.490
if you don't know this world,
the World Bank and the OECD

00:57:55.490 --> 00:57:58.700
and the UN have a lot of--

00:57:58.700 --> 00:58:00.350
not to insult
anybody, but they have

00:58:00.350 --> 00:58:03.650
