00:58:51.940 --> 00:58:55.210
And then some other papers
that I want to talk about,

00:58:55.210 --> 00:58:57.550
about some of the issues.

00:58:57.550 --> 00:59:01.610
So let me talk about just
some of the issues here.

00:59:01.610 --> 00:59:05.980
One issue that everybody
points out is absolutely right.

00:59:05.980 --> 00:59:09.160
GDP doesn't pick this up.

00:59:09.160 --> 00:59:14.545
GDP-- we talk about stocks and
flows, you have family silver,

00:59:14.545 --> 00:59:16.420
you sell the family
silver, you have a party,

00:59:16.420 --> 00:59:19.050
the party shows up in GDP.

00:59:19.050 --> 00:59:21.660
The fact that somehow the
silver's out of your hands--

00:59:21.660 --> 00:59:25.170
or it shows up in sort of
your consumption, certainly.

00:59:25.170 --> 00:59:26.308
If you burn down--

00:59:26.308 --> 00:59:28.350
and there are plenty of
African countries, plenty

00:59:28.350 --> 00:59:30.750
of other countries, that
have basically burned down--

00:59:30.750 --> 00:59:32.460
New Hampshire did
it, Vermont did it--

00:59:32.460 --> 00:59:35.640
you burn down the forest to
fuel economic development.

00:59:35.640 --> 00:59:38.970
There's a sense in which you're
changing one asset to another.

00:59:38.970 --> 00:59:41.700
Certainly, just looking
at what gets produced

00:59:41.700 --> 00:59:43.810
understates the cost.

00:59:43.810 --> 00:59:48.660
So if you look at net
national product which

00:59:48.660 --> 00:59:51.480
gets depreciation
of some assets,

00:59:51.480 --> 00:59:54.480
it subtracts from
gross national product.

00:59:54.480 --> 00:59:58.560
It picks up some of
this, but properly

00:59:58.560 --> 01:00:02.100
measured, you'd want to take
into account the fact that what

01:00:02.100 --> 01:00:04.740
happened in 19th century
Britain was they paid

01:00:04.740 --> 01:00:09.120
for economic development in part
by trashing the environment,

01:00:09.120 --> 01:00:12.480
in part by killing
people with the health

01:00:12.480 --> 01:00:15.900
effects of all that
smoke, and degrading

01:00:15.900 --> 01:00:16.900
the natural environment.

01:00:16.900 --> 01:00:19.150
So you'd want to take that
into account when you said,

01:00:19.150 --> 01:00:21.960
what's income, what are
living standards, really?

01:00:21.960 --> 01:00:23.910
We don't know how to do that.

01:00:23.910 --> 01:00:26.640
There's work at the UN,
there's work at the US.

01:00:26.640 --> 01:00:29.850
But part of the
green growth argument

01:00:29.850 --> 01:00:34.260
could be that what
you want to measure

01:00:34.260 --> 01:00:38.310
isn't GDP growth, but growth
in living standards, taking

01:00:38.310 --> 01:00:40.567
into account all
this other stuff,

01:00:40.567 --> 01:00:42.150
taking into account
changes in health,

01:00:42.150 --> 01:00:45.460
taking into account changes
in the natural environment,

01:00:45.460 --> 01:00:46.630
and so forth.

01:00:46.630 --> 01:00:50.860
So you could say, OK,
that's a relevant point.

01:00:50.860 --> 01:00:52.620
Another relevant
point is they talk

01:00:52.620 --> 01:00:58.410
about increasing investment,
taking 2% of world GDP

01:00:58.410 --> 01:01:01.900
and investing it
in green things.

01:01:01.900 --> 01:01:04.590
Well, if you make
massive investments

01:01:04.590 --> 01:01:08.520
and they're not terrible,
they will eventually

01:01:08.520 --> 01:01:10.740
raise growth, right?

01:01:10.740 --> 01:01:13.870
So you're increasing-- there
are numbers in my paper.

01:01:13.870 --> 01:01:14.620
They don't matter.

01:01:14.620 --> 01:01:16.710
But it's basically
what the UN is

01:01:16.710 --> 01:01:18.840
saying is the world
as a whole needs

01:01:18.840 --> 01:01:21.840
to make a massive increase
in green investments.

01:01:21.840 --> 01:01:23.880
If you do that, you
probably will raise growth.

01:01:23.880 --> 01:01:26.530
That doesn't mean
it's a good idea.

01:01:26.530 --> 01:01:28.360
If you doubled the
US capital formation,

01:01:28.360 --> 01:01:30.130
you'd raise us growth.

01:01:30.130 --> 01:01:31.150
A, how do you do it?

01:01:31.150 --> 01:01:33.700
B, is it actually a good deal?

01:01:33.700 --> 01:01:38.480
But the kicker here,
most of these models say,

01:01:38.480 --> 01:01:39.640
here's how we raise growth.

01:01:39.640 --> 01:01:45.292
We raise growth by reducing
environmental limits on growth.

01:01:45.292 --> 01:01:46.750
What would
environmental limits be?

01:01:46.750 --> 01:01:51.160
Well, in the limit,
everybody gets sick

01:01:51.160 --> 01:01:54.600
and production and
productivity falls off.

01:01:54.600 --> 01:01:57.640
So if you've ever
tried to breathe

01:01:57.640 --> 01:01:59.620
in large Chinese
cities, you get a sense

01:01:59.620 --> 01:02:02.630
that there is some theoretical--

01:02:02.630 --> 01:02:04.570
that this may be
more than theory

01:02:04.570 --> 01:02:08.480
in some places at some times.

01:02:08.480 --> 01:02:14.600
But globally, probably not.

01:02:14.600 --> 01:02:19.890
So two good points and one point
that's sort of OK in theory.

01:02:19.890 --> 01:02:22.470
The good points are--

01:02:22.470 --> 01:02:26.250
in terms of going
green-- that GDP growth

01:02:26.250 --> 01:02:28.920
isn't really a good measure of
growth in standards of living.

01:02:28.920 --> 01:02:33.060
It isn't a good measure of
sustainability, period--

01:02:33.060 --> 01:02:34.530
sure.

01:02:34.530 --> 01:02:36.240
Increasing the
rate of investment

01:02:36.240 --> 01:02:39.600
in green technologies
and lots of other things

01:02:39.600 --> 01:02:41.190
will raise growth.

01:02:41.190 --> 01:02:42.240
Yeah.

01:02:42.240 --> 01:02:43.650
So would investment
in railroads,

01:02:43.650 --> 01:02:45.108
so so would investment
in highways,

01:02:45.108 --> 01:02:47.010
so would investments
in education.

01:02:47.010 --> 01:02:50.130
But that's certainly true.

01:02:50.130 --> 01:02:55.200
It is possible that
one way going green

01:02:55.200 --> 01:02:58.350
increases economic growth
is by sort of reducing

01:02:58.350 --> 01:03:00.600
environmental limits.

01:03:00.600 --> 01:03:05.520
The soil's exhausted, the people
are sick, et cetera, et cetera,

01:03:05.520 --> 01:03:08.820
the aquifers are depleted,
and you're stuck.

01:03:08.820 --> 01:03:10.780
That is certainly possible.

01:03:10.780 --> 01:03:13.200
And if you're really
a pessimistic person,

01:03:13.200 --> 01:03:15.690
you can look down the
road, and climate change

01:03:15.690 --> 01:03:19.530
is another set of mechanisms
that could do this.

01:03:19.530 --> 01:03:21.270
But is it globally
quantitatively

01:03:21.270 --> 01:03:24.270
important in the near term?

01:03:24.270 --> 01:03:26.860
No evidence.

01:03:26.860 --> 01:03:27.360
OK.

01:03:32.190 --> 01:03:34.650
More relevant points.

01:03:34.650 --> 01:03:38.220
Certainly in rich countries,
you can make the argument

01:03:38.220 --> 01:03:42.210
that, yes, we should be greener
than we are, particularly

01:03:42.210 --> 01:03:43.350
in this country.

01:03:43.350 --> 01:03:46.140
If you think carbon
dioxide does anything,

01:03:46.140 --> 01:03:49.230
it probably makes
sense to switch--

01:03:49.230 --> 01:03:54.450
that understates the case to
switch to less carbon-intensive

01:03:54.450 --> 01:03:57.420
growth paths, cut
emissions, conservation,

01:03:57.420 --> 01:03:58.830
shift to natural gas.

01:03:58.830 --> 01:04:02.640
The interesting question,
and the politically tricky

01:04:02.640 --> 01:04:05.460
question, is in poor countries.

01:04:05.460 --> 01:04:06.870
Because the green
growth story is

01:04:06.870 --> 01:04:08.880
a story not about
the rich countries,

01:04:08.880 --> 01:04:12.810
it's a story about
mostly poor countries--

01:04:12.810 --> 01:04:18.420
massive investments in going
green in poor countries.

01:04:18.420 --> 01:04:21.553
Well, massive investments
in almost anything sensible

01:04:21.553 --> 01:04:23.220
in poor countries
would be a good thing.

01:04:23.220 --> 01:04:26.160
Where does it come from?

01:04:26.160 --> 01:04:29.290
Probably doesn't
come internally.

01:04:29.290 --> 01:04:31.642
This is the climate problem
revisited in a way--

01:04:31.642 --> 01:04:34.100
probably doesn't come internally
because they don't have it

01:04:34.100 --> 01:04:36.460
and they have other priorities.

01:04:36.460 --> 01:04:39.640
Again, telling the Chinese
not to use the coal

01:04:39.640 --> 01:04:42.670
while so many millions
of people live in poverty

01:04:42.670 --> 01:04:45.880
is a tough point, tough sale.

01:04:45.880 --> 01:04:47.860
Massive foreign aid?

01:04:47.860 --> 01:04:51.970
Well, appropriating
massive foreign aid--

01:04:51.970 --> 01:04:55.360
again, there's some numbers in
my paper, about $400 billion

01:04:55.360 --> 01:04:57.540
a year from the US.

01:04:57.540 --> 01:04:59.790
Imagine walking into Congress
and saying, yes, yes.

01:04:59.790 --> 01:05:02.970
I know we have problems but
we need to send $400 billion

01:05:02.970 --> 01:05:05.640
a year in foreign aid.

01:05:05.640 --> 01:05:07.830
You would not get a
vote on the floor.

01:05:07.830 --> 01:05:10.710
You would not get a
vote in a committee.

01:05:10.710 --> 01:05:12.840
And the other problem
is the history says,

01:05:12.840 --> 01:05:16.470
if you dump lots of
foreign aid on countries

01:05:16.470 --> 01:05:18.840
that don't have good
governance structures,

01:05:18.840 --> 01:05:20.640
you don't get good results.

01:05:20.640 --> 01:05:21.570
It gets stolen.

01:05:21.570 --> 01:05:23.980
It gets wasted.

01:05:23.980 --> 01:05:26.590
So that's not likely.

01:05:26.590 --> 01:05:29.490
So without the aid, how
can you possibly, say,

01:05:29.490 --> 01:05:33.510
in Africa, in particular, where
there is hydro potential, where

01:05:33.510 --> 01:05:38.180
there is coal, and where
there is a lot of poverty,

01:05:38.180 --> 01:05:39.000
why not use it?

01:05:39.000 --> 01:05:40.130
Now you can say--

01:05:40.130 --> 01:05:43.460
you could say--
actually, that's wrong.

01:05:43.460 --> 01:05:47.760
You can say the equity
issues are absolutely clear.

01:05:47.760 --> 01:05:52.110
We talked about this when we
talked about climate change.

01:05:52.110 --> 01:05:55.670
If I'm a poor country
and you say to me,

01:05:55.670 --> 01:05:59.300
we really need you to go green.

01:05:59.300 --> 01:06:03.420
I would say to you, you didn't.

01:06:03.420 --> 01:06:04.290
You got rich.

01:06:04.290 --> 01:06:05.790
You burned your coal.

01:06:05.790 --> 01:06:06.930
You cut down your trees.

01:06:06.930 --> 01:06:09.360
Why can't I?

01:06:09.360 --> 01:06:11.820
If you give me
money, maybe I won't.

01:06:11.820 --> 01:06:14.460
But maybe if you give
me money, I'll waste it.

01:06:14.460 --> 01:06:16.830
It'll go to a bank account
in Switzerland or the Cayman

01:06:16.830 --> 01:06:18.480
Islands.

01:06:18.480 --> 01:06:23.940
Or I'll hire my
brother-in-law to build a dam.

01:06:23.940 --> 01:06:26.580
So this is sort of
a terrible thing.

01:06:26.580 --> 01:06:30.360
Now this is
something that's sort

01:06:30.360 --> 01:06:32.220
of not on, as the English say.

01:06:32.220 --> 01:06:35.688
There's just no way to get it
done without massive transfers

01:06:35.688 --> 01:06:37.980
of aid, and there's no way
to get the massive transfers

01:06:37.980 --> 01:06:39.330
of aid done--

01:06:39.330 --> 01:06:43.090
as far as I can
tell, in any case.

01:06:43.090 --> 01:06:46.410
One point I do want
to make, though,

01:06:46.410 --> 01:06:50.220
and that is while you're
thinking about startups, one

01:06:50.220 --> 01:06:53.520
of the really
interesting opportunities

01:06:53.520 --> 01:06:58.620
globally is the large
number of people who

01:06:58.620 --> 01:07:01.560
have no electricity, period.

01:07:01.560 --> 01:07:04.530
Who are off-grid, who
are in rural areas.

01:07:04.530 --> 01:07:06.030
And that's one of
those interesting

01:07:06.030 --> 01:07:07.980
bottom-of-the-pyramid
opportunities that a lot

01:07:07.980 --> 01:07:11.870
of people have tried to
crack because having lighting

01:07:11.870 --> 01:07:13.980
at night makes a
huge difference.

01:07:13.980 --> 01:07:17.030
It means kids can
stay in school.

01:07:17.030 --> 01:07:20.090
It means the family can
work after the sun goes down

01:07:20.090 --> 01:07:21.140
at various things.

01:07:21.140 --> 01:07:22.880
But in particular,
kids can study.

01:07:25.930 --> 01:07:28.330
And there are a lot of
people who have tried

01:07:28.330 --> 01:07:30.700
to crack that economically.

01:07:30.700 --> 01:07:33.070
Usually some version
of solar plus storage

01:07:33.070 --> 01:07:36.040
deployed at the community
level or solar lanterns that

01:07:36.040 --> 01:07:38.770
could be sold cheaply and
charged in the daytime

01:07:38.770 --> 01:07:39.970
and used at night.

01:07:39.970 --> 01:07:42.400
So there are lots of
opportunities there.

01:07:42.400 --> 01:07:44.620
It isn't massive.

01:07:44.620 --> 01:07:47.140
It isn't massive.

01:07:47.140 --> 01:07:50.440
The other thing to point out is
one of the real tragedies here,

01:07:50.440 --> 01:07:53.440
and one of the reasons why
the whole green growth notion

01:07:53.440 --> 01:07:58.000
is compelling, but painful.

01:07:58.000 --> 01:08:03.610
And that is, again, there's
a piece on Stellar--

01:08:03.610 --> 01:08:06.130
if you ask who's going to
be harmed by climate change,

01:08:06.130 --> 01:08:09.250
it's mostly the
developing world, right?

01:08:09.250 --> 01:08:12.100
I mean, we can afford to
build a wall around Manhattan

01:08:12.100 --> 01:08:13.960
to deal with sea level rise.

01:08:13.960 --> 01:08:17.090
Bangladesh can't build a wall.

01:08:17.090 --> 01:08:18.700
But of course, the
developing world

01:08:18.700 --> 01:08:21.010
is also driving
climate change if you

01:08:21.010 --> 01:08:23.890
look at the growth in
emissions, as we talked about

01:08:23.890 --> 01:08:25.120
on several occasions.

01:08:25.120 --> 01:08:27.010
There's just no obvious fix.

01:08:27.010 --> 01:08:31.060
So the green growth is trying
to-- is an attempt by a whole

01:08:31.060 --> 01:08:36.939
set of staff people to advocate
for massive change in the way

01:08:36.939 --> 01:08:41.560
the world runs that's
probably not going to work--

01:08:41.560 --> 01:08:43.908
not going to work
politically, which

01:08:43.908 --> 01:08:46.450
is one reason why I didn't feel
like doing an hour and a half

01:08:46.450 --> 01:08:51.279
on it, because I think
the air has gone out.

01:08:51.279 --> 01:08:54.875
There will be a circus in Rio.

01:08:54.875 --> 01:08:58.240
There will probably be 100 heads
of state or government in Rio

01:08:58.240 --> 01:08:59.979
next month.

01:08:59.979 --> 01:09:05.200
I'm told hotel rooms are going
for thousands of a night,

01:09:05.200 --> 01:09:07.729
so it will be a big circus.

01:09:07.729 --> 01:09:09.880
I'm told that the
official US government

01:09:09.880 --> 01:09:12.910
position is that
Rio should produce

01:09:12.910 --> 01:09:17.350
a clean five-page statement
of principles and policies,

01:09:17.350 --> 01:09:20.830
and that the current working
draft is 260 pages long.

01:09:24.340 --> 01:09:26.200
Diplomats do this.

01:09:26.200 --> 01:09:29.410
Diplomats do this.

01:09:29.410 --> 01:09:34.630
So this is the story of
people trying to figure out

01:09:34.630 --> 01:09:37.300
what comes after the Framework
Convention on Climate

01:09:37.300 --> 01:09:40.779
Change, what comes after
thinking about sustainability.

01:09:40.779 --> 01:09:42.490
And the answer is--

01:09:42.490 --> 01:09:45.899
or was-- a major push
toward being green,

01:09:45.899 --> 01:09:48.880
please, really a
serious, major push.

01:09:48.880 --> 01:09:51.310
I think it lacks
intellectual foundation,

01:09:51.310 --> 01:09:53.470
I think it lacks
political foundation.

01:09:53.470 --> 01:09:55.960
I think it will be
much discussed at Rio

01:09:55.960 --> 01:09:58.550
and nothing will happen.

01:09:58.550 --> 01:10:01.720
I do hate the last
talk to be so cynical.

01:10:01.720 --> 01:10:05.380
Maybe we'll be hopeful next
week when we hear your papers.

01:10:05.380 --> 01:10:09.140
Do you have questions or
comments on any of this?

01:10:09.140 --> 01:10:11.750
That's sort of the-- this is
the current diplomatic state

01:10:11.750 --> 01:10:12.440
of play.

01:10:12.440 --> 01:10:15.440
This is an attempt to do
climate by the back door

01:10:15.440 --> 01:10:17.030
and call it green.

01:10:17.030 --> 01:10:20.390
It isn't going to
work, sadly, I think.

01:10:20.390 --> 01:10:21.332
Yeah, Julien?

01:10:21.332 --> 01:10:23.540
AUDIENCE: I was just curious
if you expected anything

01:10:23.540 --> 01:10:27.020
like productive at
all to come out of it?

01:10:27.020 --> 01:10:29.990
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE:
Well, you know, diplomacy

01:10:29.990 --> 01:10:31.790
is a really strange process.

01:10:31.790 --> 01:10:33.380
It's easy to mock, right?

01:10:33.380 --> 01:10:38.180
Because particularly
in climate, there's

01:10:38.180 --> 01:10:39.590
this group of
diplomats that like

01:10:39.590 --> 01:10:41.240
to get together
every couple of years

01:10:41.240 --> 01:10:44.450
and talk and make progress.

01:10:44.450 --> 01:10:49.130
But without government
support, it's all just talk.

01:10:49.130 --> 01:10:52.190
Given that the main problem
the world sees right now

01:10:52.190 --> 01:10:55.550
is slow recovery from
a deep recession,

01:10:55.550 --> 01:11:00.320
and given the current state of
politics in the US on climate,

01:11:00.320 --> 01:11:04.850
I expect lovely prose
to come out of this.

01:11:04.850 --> 01:11:07.760
There might be agreement
on something small.

01:11:07.760 --> 01:11:10.222
They might get
something on forests.

01:11:10.222 --> 01:11:12.680
I could give you my cynical
lecture about forest protection

01:11:12.680 --> 01:11:15.370
sometime.

01:11:15.370 --> 01:11:17.540
As long as you don't affect
the demand for wood--

01:11:17.540 --> 01:11:21.830
protecting this forest doesn't
reduce the amount of wood cut.

01:11:21.830 --> 01:11:25.130
But that's just the economist.

01:11:25.130 --> 01:11:27.660
I expect there will
be some agreements.

01:11:27.660 --> 01:11:29.557
I don't think they
will be very important.

01:11:32.360 --> 01:11:36.440
And as I say, I expect a circus.

01:11:36.440 --> 01:11:38.350
The folks in the
diplomatic community

01:11:38.350 --> 01:11:40.720
would say that's too cynical.

01:11:40.720 --> 01:11:45.190
Even just talking with
the whole world involved,

01:11:45.190 --> 01:11:47.830
putting a spotlight
on these issues,

01:11:47.830 --> 01:11:51.430
keeping up pressure of
some international kind

01:11:51.430 --> 01:11:54.670
on governments that
don't want to act helps.

01:11:54.670 --> 01:11:59.410
Sort of the water on a
stone view of the world.

01:11:59.410 --> 01:12:00.760
That's what they do.

01:12:00.760 --> 01:12:02.890
And every so often,
there will be a chance.

01:12:02.890 --> 01:12:04.210
You'll get the Montreal--

01:12:04.210 --> 01:12:07.090
you'll get the Montreal Protocol
on ozone depleting gases

01:12:07.090 --> 01:12:10.090
because that
process had started.

01:12:10.090 --> 01:12:11.900
Those meetings were being held.

01:12:11.900 --> 01:12:14.380
New science came, the
structure was in place,

01:12:14.380 --> 01:12:16.480
the support mobilized, bang.

01:12:16.480 --> 01:12:18.790
We got a very constructive
international agreement.

01:12:18.790 --> 01:12:21.100
It isn't going to happen here
because the preconditions

01:12:21.100 --> 01:12:23.140
aren't there.

01:12:23.140 --> 01:12:26.725
But the water will
drip on the stone.

01:12:26.725 --> 01:12:28.100
The water will
drip on the stone.

01:12:28.100 --> 01:12:28.850
Rory?

01:12:28.850 --> 01:12:31.910
AUDIENCE: Has anyone-- well,
[INAUDIBLE] response to--

01:12:31.910 --> 01:12:35.255
he was saying, the rich world
didn't follow a green growth

01:12:35.255 --> 01:12:37.310
path, but they followed
the greenest growth

01:12:37.310 --> 01:12:40.340
path available to them at
the time within economics.

01:12:40.340 --> 01:12:43.343
And you could argue that
Britain, if they could have,

01:12:43.343 --> 01:12:45.260
Britain wouldn't have
covered all their cities

01:12:45.260 --> 01:12:46.730
in smog and soot.

01:12:46.730 --> 01:12:47.850
But they couldn't.

01:12:47.850 --> 01:12:51.740
The growth is good
for its own sake.

01:12:51.740 --> 01:12:54.290
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE: Yeah.

01:12:54.290 --> 01:12:57.060
That's a decent debating point.

01:12:57.060 --> 01:13:00.410
But you also say, when
did the rich world

01:13:00.410 --> 01:13:03.880
begin to take the
environment seriously?

01:13:03.880 --> 01:13:07.580
And when did it begin to
have any impact on policy?

01:13:07.580 --> 01:13:10.980
And that's sort of
'60s, '70s, right?

01:13:10.980 --> 01:13:12.240
You don't see much--

01:13:12.240 --> 01:13:14.870
you don't see much
conscious thinking about it.

01:13:18.040 --> 01:13:23.060
The big US event was DDT and
Rachel Carson's Silent Spring,

01:13:23.060 --> 01:13:25.820
which was-- do you remember?

01:13:25.820 --> 01:13:26.600
'57?

01:13:26.600 --> 01:13:27.470
'62?

01:13:27.470 --> 01:13:30.250
Around there-- around there.

01:13:30.250 --> 01:13:32.903
Birds were dying because DDT
was making their shells too thin

01:13:32.903 --> 01:13:34.070
and they couldn't reproduce.

01:13:34.070 --> 01:13:36.195
That was like oh my God,
our chemicals are actually

01:13:36.195 --> 01:13:37.430
doing something out there.

01:13:37.430 --> 01:13:40.148
But to most people, better
things through better

01:13:40.148 --> 01:13:41.190
living through chemistry.

01:13:41.190 --> 01:13:44.000
So to argue that we were
doing the best we could

01:13:44.000 --> 01:13:46.790
is to argue that we were
doing it unconsciously.

01:13:46.790 --> 01:13:50.210
And that may be
true, but it's not--

01:13:50.210 --> 01:13:51.910
that's not that persuasive.

01:13:51.910 --> 01:13:53.840
It's a good shot, though.

01:13:53.840 --> 01:13:54.740
Anything else?

01:13:54.740 --> 01:13:57.750
Anything else on your minds?

